<TITLE> Another swine flu case takes total detected to 25 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 19 (bdnews24.com)Another confirmed case of swine flu in Bangladesh brought the total recorded cases to 25 on Wednesday, an official said. IEDCR director Mahmudur Rahman told bdnews24.com the latest case to be detected was a 36 year-old male recently returned from Singapore. Rahman said earlier cases detected in Bangladeshis had recently arrived from the Britain, Canada and Australia, but most cases were from the United States. A handful of the previous 24 cases have been contracted in the country. The World Health Organisation declared a global swine flu pandemic on June 11 while the health ministry confirmed the first case in Bangladesh on June 19. WHO said 125,000 laboratory cases have been confirmed and gave a death toll of 700 on Wednesday. The UN agency has said it is up to national health authorities to decide what measures they impose to slow the spread of the new strain, but it also told countries to stop reporting individual cases and concentrate on mitigation measures and detecting any unusual patterns of disease or spike in rates of absenteeism. The world health body said this is the fastest-moving pandemic ever and it is now pointless to count every case. As a mitigationmeasure, the Bangladesh government is screening incoming international passengers for flu symptoms at Dhaka, Chittagong and Sylhet airports. Chittagong and Mongla seaports and 11 land ports are also on the lookout, according to officials. Symptoms of the virus include fever with high temperature and respiratory problems. The IEDCR advises schools and offices to grant leave to anyone who displays symptoms of the flu. It also advises people to refrain from spitting and to wash hands regularly to curb the spread of the swine flu virus. bd
